Bayesian Learning for Neural Networks¶

Probabilistic Programming (Project 2)¶

Sotir Anca-Nicoleta, group 407

In this project I will present the implementation of Bayesian Neural Networks in Pyro for classification tasks:

  • a linearly separable binary classification problem - the 'sanity check'
  • a non-linearly separable binary classification problem
  • a multinomial classification problem

The datasets used for these three problems are all artificial, generated either by applying some formula (first case) or by using the sklearn.datasets module.

In all cases where a bayesian network is implemented, a corresponding classic neural network was also implemented to compare their results.

def multiple_marker_style_scatter(x, y, marker_style, ax = None, **kw):
    '''
    This allows to use multiple marker styles (for example, when plotting classification results, 
    each class can have a different marker style)
    '''
    if ax is not None: 
        scatter_plot = ax.scatter(x, y, **kw)
    else:
        scatter_plot = plt.scatter(x, y, **kw)
    paths = []
    for m in marker_style:
        marker_obj = markers.MarkerStyle(m)
        path = marker_obj.get_path().transformed(marker_obj.get_transform())
        paths.append(path)
    scatter_plot.set_paths(paths)
    return scatter_plot

def plot_decision_boundary(test_data, test_labels, network_type, model, guide = None, num_samples = 1000):
    '''
    This is useful after training a model, to see if it learned a good separation of the data.
    It works by creating all possible points in a certain 2D range and then predicting their labels.
    It also plots the test data and their correct labels.
    '''
    # firstly the range is considered to be determined by the test data min-max range on the xy-axis
    xmin = test_data[:,0].min().item()
    xmax = test_data[:,0].max().item()
    ymin = test_data[:,1].min().item()
    ymax = test_data[:,1].max().item()
    # then 100 equally distanced points are considered in that x-axis range and y-axis range respectively
    xs = np.linspace(xmin, xmax, 100)
    ys = np.linspace(ymin, ymax, 100)
    # the cartesian product of those coordinates is computed to find all points in that square
    comb = np.transpose([np.tile(xs, len(ys)), np.repeat(ys, len(xs))])
    comb = torch.from_numpy(comb).type(torch.float32)
    xs = comb[:,0]
    ys = comb[:,1]
    # obtaining results differs based on the neural network type ('bayesian' or 'classic')
    if network_type == 'bayesian':
        predictive = Predictive(model, guide = guide, num_samples = num_samples)
        data = predictive(comb) 
        predictions = data.get('result').detach().numpy() # fetch the labels from the model
        predictions = np.asarray(np.round(np.mean(predictions, axis = 0)), dtype = 'int')
    if network_type == 'classic':
        with torch.no_grad(): # no need to compute gradients when testing
            output = model(comb)
        predictions = np.argmax(output, axis = 1)
    # plot the network's predictions
    label_colors = np.array(['purple', 'orange','royalblue','lightseagreen'])
    label_markers = np.array(['o', 'o','o','o'])
    plt.figure(figsize = (10, 10))
    plt.title('Neural Network Decision Boundary')
    multiple_marker_style_scatter(xs, ys, label_markers[predictions], color = label_colors[predictions], alpha = 0.1)
    multiple_marker_style_scatter(test_data[:, 0], test_data[:, 1], label_markers[test_labels], color = label_colors[test_labels])
    plt.show()

def generate_data(samples_no):
  X = np.random.randn(samples_no, 2) # generating random 2D input values
  Y = np.tanh(X[:, 0] + X[:, 1])     # this is the value computed by a node on the hidden layer
  Y = 1 / (1 + np.exp(-(Y + Y)))     # applying sigmoid function
  Y = Y > 0.5                        # label 1 if sigmoid is greater than 0.5, else 0
  return X, Y.astype(int)            # return samples_no such points and their labels

The Bayesian Neural Network¶

To implement the Bayesian Network, a prior over the network's parameters must be defined. Then, during inference, good parameter values can be learned starting from it.

In Bayesian Learning for Neural Networks, by Radford M. Neal, I found the piece of information displayed below. Because of this, I decided to use as prior for the parameters of the Bayesian Networks implemented in this notebook a Normal distribution of mean 0 and standard deviation 1 .

In [10]:
display_drive_image('/content/drive/MyDrive/PP/Project2/images/params-prior-dist.PNG', figsize = (20, 20))

Next we need to define the bayesian neural network. It can be seen that instead of just using the nn.Linear layer from Pytorch (i.e. what we would use in a classic neural network), it is wrapped by a PyroModule and its weights are sampled from the prior distribution of Normal(0, 1).

In [11]:
class BNN(PyroModule):
    
    # define the initialization method which creates the network's layers
    def __init__(self, input_size, hidden_size, output_size):
        super().__init__()
        # the hidden fully connected layer
        self.fc1 = PyroModule[nn.Linear](input_size, hidden_size, bias = False)
        self.fc1.weight = PyroSample(dist.Normal(0., 1.).expand([hidden_size, input_size]).to_event(2))
        # the output layer
        self.out = PyroModule[nn.Linear](hidden_size, output_size, bias = False)
        self.out.weight = PyroSample(dist.Normal(0., 1.).expand([output_size, hidden_size]).to_event(2))
    
    # define the way of passing the input through the network
    def forward(self, x, y = None):
        x = self.fc1(x)
        x = torch.tanh(x)
        x = self.out(x)
        p1 = torch.sigmoid(x) # a value between 0 and 1 for each input entry
        # p1 is the probability of the input to produce a label of value 1

        # also deduce the probability of the input to produce a label of value 0
        # thus, p will be given to a Categorical distribution for the label
        p = torch.randn(x.shape[0], 2)
        for i in range(len(p1)):
            p[i][0] = 1 - p1[i]
            p[i][1] = p1[i]

        # using plate because data is given in batchez, not individual entries
        with pyro.plate("data", x.shape[0]):
            result = pyro.sample("result", dist.Categorical(p), obs = y) # note the obs is given for inference
            # the resulting labels are given by a Categorical distribution
            # for training, the labels will be given to this method and they will be marked as observed variable
        return result

It can be seen in the plot above that the weigths are all centered at -1 (their mean is -1). It is visible that they are of Normal distribution, but their weights changed during inference from mean 0 to mean -1.

An observation would be that the initial dataaset was computed with all weights being fixed to a value of 1, so why is it that they were optimized to -1?

In [20]:
x = torch.from_numpy(np.linspace(-5, 5, 100))
y = torch.tanh(x)
plt.figure(figsize = (15, 5))
plt.plot([0]*100, np.linspace(-1, 1, 100), color = 'black', linewidth = 1)
plt.plot(x, [0]*100, color = 'black', linewidth = 1)
plt.plot(x, y, color = 'purple', linewidth = 2, label = '')
plt.grid(True, 'both', alpha = 0.25)
plt.title('Hyperbolic tangent (tanh)')
plt.xlabel('x')
plt.ylabel('tanh(x)')
plt.show()

As it can be seen in the Hyperbolic tangent function's plot, $tanh(x) = -tanh(-x)$ (it is a symmetric - odd - function).

Data was generated in the following manner:

$y = sigmoid(tanh(x_1w_{11} + x_2w_{12}) \cdot w_{31} + tanh(x_1w_{21} + x_2w_{22}) \cdot w_{32})$

For weights fixed to 1, the equations becomes: $y = sigmoid(2 \cdot tanh(x_1 + x_2)) $

For weights fixed to -1, the equations becomes: $y = sigmoid(-2 \cdot tanh(-x_1 - x_2)) $

Because $tanh(x) = -tanh(-x)$ , we can say that $tanh(x_1 + x_2) = -tanh(-x_1 - x_2)$. Thus, we obtain the same result with parameters fixed to 1 and to -1.

The Classic Neural Network¶

Next will be implemented a Classic Neural Network corresponding to the Bayesian one implemented above. I tried to achieve the best results I could get with a similar architecture to compare their results accordingly.

It was also implemented in PyTorch.

In [51]:
class NN(nn.Module):

    # initialize the networks layers 
    #(note that no probabilistic programming wrapper was used in this one)
    def __init__(self, input_size, hidden_size, output_size):
        super(NN, self).__init__()
        self.fc1 = nn.Linear(input_size, hidden_size, bias = False)
        self.out = nn.Linear(hidden_size, output_size, bias = False)

    # no more random variables
    # only pass the imput through the layers and return a probability for each class
    def forward(self, x):
        x = self.fc1(x)
        x = torch.tanh(x)
        x = self.out(x)
        p1 = torch.sigmoid(x)
        p = torch.randn(x.shape[0], 2)
        for i in range(len(p1)):
            p[i][0] = 1 - p1[i]
            p[i][1] = p1[i]
        return p

# the higher the probability, the lower the corresponding negative log likelihood
lossf = nn.NLLLoss()

epoch_no = 500
loss_history = []

for e in range(epoch_no):
    optimizer.zero_grad() # clear the gradient buffers
    output = net(train_data) # pass the training data (no labels are passed because no inference)
    loss = lossf(output, train_labels) # compute the loss on the results
    if (e + 1) % 25 == 0: # print progress every few epochs
      print("Epoch", str(e + 1).ljust(5), "Loss", loss.item())
    loss_history.append(loss)
    loss.backward() # backpropagate the loss
    optimizer.step() # make changes to the network's parameters

It can be observed that the network's weights are as follows:

$w_{11} \approx w_{12} \approx 2$

$w_{31} \approx 3$

$w_{21} \approx w_{22} \approx -2$

$w_{31} \approx -3$

Through similar computations as before, it could be seen that the result stays the same as for the Bayesian network because, even though the weights are not 1 or -1, the result of the sigmoid is the same.

Intuitively, a negative number multiplied by a positive number is even smaller; a positive number multiplied by a positive number is even greater. That is why the network learned such weights as 2, -2, 3, -3 as opposed to just -1, 1, which can be seen as a degree of certainty (larger negative values will result in smaller probability given by sigmoid, while larger positive values will result in greater probability given by sigmoid).

The Bayesian Neural Network¶

Again, a Bayesian Neural Network is implemented. The difference from the first network is adding a second hidden layer, as the problem is definitely more complex than the first linearly separable one. Otherwise, the code is very similar to the first case.

In [64]:
class BNN(PyroModule):
    
    # initialize network layers
    # this network has two hidden layers of the same size
    def __init__(self, input_size, hidden_size, output_size):
        
        super().__init__()
        self.fc1 = PyroModule[nn.Linear](input_size, hidden_size)
        self.fc1.weight = PyroSample(dist.Normal(0., 1.).expand([hidden_size, input_size]).to_event(2))
        self.fc1.bias = PyroSample(dist.Normal(0., 1.).expand([hidden_size]))

        self.fc2 = PyroModule[nn.Linear](hidden_size, hidden_size)
        self.fc2.weight = PyroSample(dist.Normal(0., 1.).expand([hidden_size, hidden_size]).to_event(2))
        self.fc2.bias = PyroSample(dist.Normal(0., 1.).expand([hidden_size]))

        self.out = PyroModule[nn.Linear](hidden_size, output_size)
        self.out.weight = PyroSample(dist.Normal(0., 1.).expand([output_size, hidden_size]).to_event(2))
        self.out.bias = PyroSample(dist.Normal(0., 1.).expand([output_size]))

    # define how input is passed through the network
    def forward(self, x, y = None):
        x = torch.tanh(self.fc1(x))
        x = torch.tanh(self.fc2(x))
        x = self.out(x)
        p = torch.softmax(x, dim = 1)

        # in case the labels are passed, they are considered observed variables
        with pyro.plate("data", x.shape[0]):
            result = pyro.sample("result", dist.Categorical(p), obs = y)
        
        return result

The Classic Neural Network¶

A classic neural network of the same architecture as the bayesian network was also trained:

In [75]:
class NN(nn.Module):

    # initialize network's layers
    # this network also contains two hidden layers
    def __init__(self, input_size, hidden_size1, hidden_size2, output_size):
        super(NN, self).__init__()
        self.fc1 = nn.Linear(input_size, hidden_size1)
        self.fc2 = nn.Linear(hidden_size1, hidden_size2)
        self.out = nn.Linear(hidden_size2, output_size)

    # define how input is passed through the network
    def forward(self, x):
        x = torch.tanh(self.fc1(x))
        x = torch.tanh(self.fc2(x))
        x = self.out(x)
        return x

      print("Epoch", str(e + 1).ljust(5), "Loss", loss.item())
    loss_history.append(loss)
    loss.backward() # backpropagate the loss
    optimizer.step() # modify parameters accordingly

The Bayesian Neural Network¶

Surprisingly, I achieved somewhat good results on this dataset using only one hidden layer in both these networks. Again, the code is very similar to the one for the first two problems.

In [104]:
class BNN(PyroModule):

    # initialize the network's layers
    def __init__(self, input_size, hidden_size, output_size):
        super().__init__()
        self.fc1 = PyroModule[nn.Linear](input_size, hidden_size)
        self.fc1.weight = PyroSample(dist.Normal(0., 1.).expand([hidden_size, input_size]).to_event(2))
        self.fc1.bias = PyroSample(dist.Normal(0., 1.).expand([hidden_size]))

        self.out = PyroModule[nn.Linear](hidden_size, output_size)
        self.out.weight = PyroSample(dist.Normal(0., 1.).expand([output_size, hidden_size]).to_event(2))
        self.out.bias = PyroSample(dist.Normal(0., 1.).expand([output_size]))

    # define how input is passed through the network
    # if provided, y is the observed variable        
    def forward(self, x, y = None):
        x = torch.tanh(self.fc1(x))
        x = self.out(x)
        p = torch.softmax(x, dim = 1)

        with pyro.plate("data", x.shape[0]):
            result = pyro.sample("result", dist.Categorical(p), obs = y)
        
        return result

    output = net(train_data)
    loss = lossf(output, train_labels) # compute loss
    if (e + 1) % 100 == 0: # print progress every few epochs
      print("Epoch", str(e + 1).ljust(5), "Loss", loss.item())
    loss_history.append(loss)
    loss.backward() # backpropagate the loss
    optimizer.step() # modify weights accordingly

Extra Experiment: Inference on network architecture¶

I had an idea of introducing a categorical parameter in the bayesian networks with the purpose of finding a good hidden layer size. Thus, the hidden layer size would also be inferred.

To start with, I wanted to see if it works for the sanity check. Next, the question would be: could the bayesian network for the multinomial classification (which got 80% accuracy) be improved?

Sanity Check (Again)¶

Generate data¶

In [164]:
def generate_data(samples_no):
  X = np.random.randn(samples_no, 2) # generating random 2D input values
  Y = np.tanh(X[:, 0] + X[:, 1])     # this is the value computed by a node on the hidden layer
  Y = 1 / (1 + np.exp(-(Y + Y)))     # applying sigmoid function
  Y = Y > 0.5                        # label 1 if sigmoid is greater than 0.5, else 0
  return X, Y.astype(int)            # return samples_no such points and their labels

The Bayesian Neural Network¶

In [175]:
class BNN(PyroModule):
    
    # define the initialization method which creates the network's layers
    def __init__(self, input_size, output_size):
        super().__init__()
        
        # the probabilities for each possible size (0 for size 0)
        p_hidden = torch.randn(6)
        p_hidden[0] = 0
        for i in range(1, 6): # possible hidden layer sizes: 1, 2, 3, 4, 5
          p_hidden[i] = 0.2

        # infer the size of the hidden layer
        self.hidden_size = PyroSample(dist.Categorical(p_hidden))
        hidden_size = self.hidden_size

        # the hidden fully connected layer
        self.fc1 = PyroModule[nn.Linear](input_size, hidden_size, bias = False)
        self.fc1.weight = PyroSample(dist.Normal(0., 1.).expand([hidden_size, input_size]).to_event(2))
        # the output layer
        self.out = PyroModule[nn.Linear](hidden_size, output_size, bias = False)
        self.out.weight = PyroSample(dist.Normal(0., 1.).expand([output_size, hidden_size]).to_event(2))
    
    # define the way of passing the input through the network
    def forward(self, x, y = None):
        x = self.fc1(x)
        x = torch.tanh(x)
        x = self.out(x)
        p1 = torch.sigmoid(x) # a value between 0 and 1 for each input entry
        # p1 is the probability of the input to produce a label of value 1

        # also deduce the probability of the input to produce a label of value 0
        # thus, p will be given to a Categorical distribution for the label
        p = torch.randn(x.shape[0], 2)
        for i in range(len(p1)):
            p[i][0] = 1 - p1[i]
            p[i][1] = p1[i]

        # using plate because data is given in batchez, not individual entries
        with pyro.plate("data", x.shape[0]):
            result = pyro.sample("result", dist.Categorical(p), obs = y) # note the obs is given for inference
            # the resulting labels are given by a Categorical distribution
            # for training, the labels will be given to this method and they will be marked as observed variable
        return result

class BNN(PyroModule):
    
    # initialize the network's layers
    def __init__(self, input_size, output_size):
        super().__init__()
        
        # the probabilities for each possible hidden layer size
        p_hidden = torch.randn(9)
        p_hidden[0] = 0
        for i in range(1, 9): # possible sizes: 1, 2, 3, ..., 8
          p_hidden[i] = 0.125

        # infer the size of the hidden layer
        self.hidden_size = PyroSample(dist.Categorical(p_hidden))
        # self.hidden_size = pyro.sample('hidden_size', dist.Categorical(p_hidden))
        hidden_size = self.hidden_size.type(torch.int32).item()


        self.fc1 = PyroModule[nn.Linear](input_size, hidden_size)
        self.fc1.weight = PyroSample(dist.Normal(0., 1.).expand([hidden_size, input_size]).to_event(2))
        self.fc1.bias = PyroSample(dist.Normal(0., 1.).expand([hidden_size]))

        self.out = PyroModule[nn.Linear](hidden_size, output_size)
        self.out.weight = PyroSample(dist.Normal(0., 1.).expand([output_size, hidden_size]).to_event(2))
        self.out.bias = PyroSample(dist.Normal(0., 1.).expand([output_size]))
        
        
    # define how input is passed through the network
    # if provided, y is the observed variable        
    def forward(self, x, y = None):
        x = torch.tanh(self.fc1(x))
        x = self.out(x)
        p = torch.softmax(x, dim = 1)

        with pyro.plate("data", x.shape[0]):
            result = pyro.sample("result", dist.Categorical(p), obs = y)
        
        return result

Conclusion of the experiment¶

It was interesting to see what hidden layer size was chosen for the network. Unfortunately, in the case of only one hidden layer, the difference is really not significant.

However, it is good to know that the experiment is not meaningless. In the case of more complex networks, with many hidden layers and a greater number of neurons per layer, the change may be much more meaningful.
